@sen561   But my tables further show that, in any limited country, the species which are the most common, that is abound most in individuals, and the species which are most widely diffused within their own country, [and this is a different consideration from wide range, and to a certain extent from commonness], oftenest give rise to varieties sufficiently well-marked to have been recorded in botanical works.

              " (extract-fr) part 12 of Darwin about: same genus, incipient species, well-marked varieties, each other, general rule, natural selection, smaller genera, larger genera, permanent varieties, any country, struggle for existence, divergence of character, have been formed, rank of species

@sen562   Hence it is the most flourishing, as they may be called, the dominant species--those which range widely, are the most diffused in their own country, and are the most numerous in individuals--which oftenest produce well-marked varieties, as I consider them, incipient species.

