@sen990   In the first place, I have collected so large a body of facts, and made so many experiments, showing, in accordance with the almost universal belief of breeders, that with animals and plants a cross between different varieties, or between individuals of the same variety but of another strain, gives vigour and fertility to the offspring, and on the other hand, that CLOSE interbreeding diminishes vigour and fertility, that these facts alone incline me to believe that it is a general law of nature that no organic being fertilises itself for a perpetuity of generations, but that a cross with another individual is occasionally--perhaps at long intervals of time--indispensable.

