              " (extract-fr) part 30 of Darwin about: other hand, has remarked, natural selection, this condition, effects of disuse

@sen1380   As the larger ground-feeding birds seldom take flight except to escape danger, it is probable that the nearly wingless condition of several birds, now inhabiting or which lately inhabited several oceanic islands, tenanted by no beasts of prey, has been caused by disuse.

              " (extract-fr) part 30 of Darwin about: other hand, has remarked, natural selection, this condition, effects of disuse

