              " (extract-fr) part 30 of Darwin about: other hand, has remarked, natural selection, this condition, effects of disuse

@sen1388   Hence, it will perhaps be safest to look at the entire absence of the anterior tarsi in Ateuchus, and their rudimentary condition in some other genera, not as cases of inherited mutilations, but as due to the effects of long-continued disuse, for as many dung-feeding beetles are generally found with their tarsi lost, this must happen early in life, therefore the tarsi cannot be of much importance or be much used by these insects.

              " (extract-fr) part 30 of Darwin about: other hand, has remarked, natural selection, this condition, effects of disuse

