@sen1890   SPECIAL DIFFICULTIES OF THE THEORY OF NATURAL SELECTION.

              " (extract-fr) part 42 of Darwin about: common progenitor, natural selection, graduated steps, this volume, closely similar

@sen1892   One of the most serious is that of neuter insects, which are often differently constructed from either the males or fertile females, but this case will be treated of in the next chapter.

              " (extract-fr) part 42 of Darwin about: common progenitor, natural selection, graduated steps, this volume, closely similar

@sen1895   In the gymnotus and torpedo they no doubt serve as powerful means of defence, and perhaps for securing prey, yet in the ray, as observed by Matteucci, an analogous organ in the tail manifests but little electricity, even when the animal is greatly irritated, so little that it can hardly be of any use for the above purposes.

              " (extract-fr) part 42 of Darwin about: common progenitor, natural selection, graduated steps, this volume, closely similar

@sen1900   Radcliffe insists, "in the electrical apparatus of the torpedo during rest, there would seem to be a charge in every respect like that which is met with in muscle and nerve during the rest, and the discharge of the torpedo, instead of being peculiar, may be only another form of the discharge which attends upon the action of muscle and motor nerve., Beyond this we cannot at present go in the way of explanation, but as we know so little about the uses of these organs, and as we know nothing about the habits and structure of the progenitors of the existing electric fishes, it would be extremely bold to maintain that no serviceable transitions are possible by which these organs might have been gradually developed.

              " (extract-fr) part 42 of Darwin about: common progenitor, natural selection, graduated steps, this volume, closely similar

@sen1902   When the same organ is found in several members of the same class, especially if in members having very different habits of life, we may generally attribute its presence to inheritance from a common ancestor, and its absence in some of the members to loss through disuse or natural selection.

