@sen2116   A much more serious objection has been urged by Bronn, and recently by Broca, namely, that many characters appear to be of no service whatever to their possessors, and therefore cannot have been influenced through natural selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2118   With respect to plants, this subject has been discussed by Nageli in an admirable essay.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2119   He admits that natural selection has effected much, but he insists that the families of plants differ chiefly from each other in morphological characters, which appear to be quite unimportant for the welfare of the species.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2125   In the second place, it should always be borne in mind that when one part is modified, so will be other parts, through certain dimly seen causes, such as an increased or diminished flow of nutriment to a part, mutual pressure, an early developed part affecting one subsequently developed, and so forth--as well as through other causes which lead to the many mysterious cases of correlation, which we do not in the least understand.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2127   In the third place, we have to allow for the direct and definite action of changed conditions of life, and for so-called spontaneous variations, in which the nature of the conditions apparently plays a quite subordinate part.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2128   Bud-variations, such as the appearance of a moss-rose on a common rose, or of a nectarine on a peach-tree, offer good instances of spontaneous variations, but even in these cases, if we bear in mind the power of a minute drop of poison in producing complex galls, we ought not to feel too sure that the above variations are not the effect of some local change in the nature of the sap, due to some change in the conditions.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2129   There must be some efficient cause for each slight individual difference, as well as for more strongly marked variations which occasionally arise, and if the unknown cause were to act persistently, it is almost certain that all the individuals of the species would be similarly modified.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2131   But it is impossible to attribute to this cause the innumerable structures which are so well adapted to the habits of life of each species.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2134   With respect to the assumed inutility of various parts and organs, it is hardly necessary to observe that even in the higher and best-known animals many structures exist, which are so highly developed that no one doubts that they are of importance, yet their use has not been, or has only recently been, ascertained.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

@sen2138   With respect to plants, to which on account of Nageli's essay I shall confine myself in the following remarks, it will be admitted that the flowers of the orchids present a multitude of curious structures, which a few years ago would have been considered as mere morphological differences without any special function, but they are now known to be of the highest importance for the fertilisation of the species through the aid of insects, and have probably been gained through natural selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 47 of Darwin about: other plants, same plant, natural selection, closed flowers, through natural selection, some other plants

