@sen2934   How the workers have been rendered sterile is a difficulty, but not much greater than that of any other striking modification of structure, for it can be shown that some insects and other articulate animals in a state of nature occasionally become sterile, and if such insects had been social, and it had been profitable to the community that a number should have been annually born capable of work, but incapable of procreation, I can see no especial difficulty in this having been effected through natural selection.

              " (extract-fr) part 65 of Darwin about: each other, natural selection, same nest, fertile females, state of nature, into each other

@sen2938   If a working ant or other neuter insect had been an ordinary animal, I should have unhesitatingly assumed that all its characters had been slowly acquired through natural selection, namely, by individuals having been born with slight profitable modifications, which were inherited by the offspring, and that these again varied and again were selected, and so onwards.

              " (extract-fr) part 65 of Darwin about: each other, natural selection, same nest, fertile females, state of nature, into each other

