@sen3166   In the first place, it may be remarked that species inhabiting distinct regions are often sterile when crossed, now it could clearly have been of no advantage to such separated species to have been rendered mutually sterile, and consequently this could not have been effected through natural selection, but it may perhaps be argued, that, if a species was rendered sterile with some one compatriot, sterility with other species would follow as a necessary contingency.

