@sen4167   The identity of many plants and animals, on mountain-summits, separated from each other by hundreds of miles of lowlands, where Alpine species could not possibly exist, is one of the most striking cases known of the same species living at distant points, without the apparent possibility of their having migrated from one point to the other.

              " (extract-fr) part 92 of Darwin about: distinct species, glacial period, united states, each other, glacial epoch, atlantic ocean, new worlds, gigantic moraines, cold period, from each other, plants and animals, round the world, spaces of ocean, whole atlantic ocean, former cold period

@sen4168   It is indeed a remarkable fact to see so many plants of the same species living on the snowy regions of the Alps or Pyrenees, and in the extreme northern parts of Europe, but it is far more remarkable, that the plants on the White Mountains, in the United States of America, are all the same with those of Labrador, and nearly all the same, as we hear from Asa Gray, with those on the loftiest mountains of Europe.

              " (extract-fr) part 92 of Darwin about: distinct species, glacial period, united states, each other, glacial epoch, atlantic ocean, new worlds, gigantic moraines, cold period, from each other, plants and animals, round the world, spaces of ocean, whole atlantic ocean, former cold period

@sen4169   Even as long ago as 1747, such facts led Gmelin to conclude that the same species must have been independently created at many distinct points, and we might have remained in this same belief, had not Agassiz and others called vivid attention to the Glacial period, which, as we shall immediately see, affords a simple explanation of these facts.

              " (extract-fr) part 92 of Darwin about: distinct species, glacial period, united states, each other, glacial epoch, atlantic ocean, new worlds, gigantic moraines, cold period, from each other, plants and animals, round the world, spaces of ocean, whole atlantic ocean, former cold period

