@sen4210   Hence, it has come, that when we compare the now living productions of the temperate regions of the New and Old Worlds, we find very few identical species, [though Asa Gray has lately shown that more plants are identical than was formerly supposed], but we find in every great class many forms, which some naturalists rank as geographical races, and others as distinct species, and a host of closely allied or representative forms which are ranked by all naturalists as specifically distinct.

              " (extract-fr) part 93 of Darwin about: glacial period, each other, from each other, america and europe, north and south

@sen4211   As on the land, so in the waters of the sea, a slow southern migration of a marine fauna, which, during the Pliocene or even a somewhat earlier period, was nearly uniform along the continuous shores of the Polar Circle, will account, on the theory of modification, for many closely allied forms now living in marine areas completely sundered.

              " (extract-fr) part 93 of Darwin about: glacial period, each other, from each other, america and europe, north and south

@sen4212   Thus, I think, we can understand the presence of some closely allied, still existing and extinct tertiary forms, on the eastern and western shores of temperate North America, and the still more striking fact of many closely allied crustaceans, [as described in Dana's admirable work], some fish and other marine animals, inhabiting the Mediterranean and the seas of Japan--these two areas being now completely separated by the breadth of a whole continent and by wide spaces of ocean.

