@sen4886   It is the pupa, and not the larva, of the Chironomus which has this power, and Grimm further shows that this case, to a certain extent, "unites that of the Cecidomyia with the parthenogenesis of the Coccidae, the term parthenogenesis implying that the mature females of the Coccidae are capable of producing fertile eggs without the concourse of the male.

              " (extract-fr) part 108 of Darwin about: each other, growth alike, stages of development, later in life

