              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4922   In some whole groups of animals and in certain members of other groups this is the case, and the embryo does not at any period differ widely from the adult, thus Owen has remarked in regard to cuttle-fish, "there is no metamorphosis, the cephalopodic character is manifested long before the parts of the embryo are completed., Land-shells and fresh-water crustaceans are born having their proper forms, while the marine members of the same two great classes pass through considerable and often great changes during their development.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4924   The larvae of most insects pass through a worm-like stage, whether they are active and adapted to diversified habits, or are inactive from being placed in the midst of proper nutriment, or from being fed by their parents, but in some few cases, as in that of Aphis, if we look to the admirable drawings of the development of this insect, by Professor Huxley, we see hardly any trace of the vermiform stage.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4926   Thus, Fritz Muller has made the remarkable discovery that certain shrimp-like crustaceans, [allied to Penoeus], first appear under the simple nauplius-form, and after passing through two or more zoea-stages, and then through the mysis-stage, finally acquire their mature structure, now in the whole great malacostracan order, to which these crustaceans belong, no other member is as yet known to be first developed under the nauplius-form, though many appear as zoeas, nevertheless Muller assigns reasons for his belief, that if there had been no suppression of development, all these crustaceans would have appeared as nauplii.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4927   How, then, can we explain these several facts in embryology--namely, the very general, though not universal, difference in structure between the embryo and the adult, the various parts in the same individual embryo, which ultimately become very unlike, and serve for diverse purposes, being at an early period of growth alike, the common, but not invariable, resemblance between the embryos or larvae of the most distinct species in the same class, the embryo often retaining, while within the egg or womb, structures which are of no service to it, either at that or at a later period of life, on the other hand, larvae which have to provide for their own wants, being perfectly adapted to the surrounding conditions, and lastly, the fact of certain larvae standing higher in the scale of organisation than the mature animal into which they are developed?

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4929   It is commonly assumed, perhaps from monstrosities affecting the embryo at a very early period, that slight variations or individual differences necessarily appear at an equally early period.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4930   We have little evidence on this head, but what we have certainly points the other way, for it is notorious that breeders of cattle, horses and various fancy animals, cannot positively tell, until some time after birth, what will be the merits and demerits of their young animals.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4937   Certain variations can only appear at corresponding ages, for instance, peculiarities in the caterpillar, cocoon, or imago states of the silk-moth, again, in the full-grown horns of cattle.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4938   But variations which, for all that we can see might have appeared either earlier or later in life, likewise tend to reappear at a corresponding age in the offspring and parent.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4939   I am far from meaning that this is invariably the case, and I could give several exceptional cases of variations, [taking the word in the largest sense], which have supervened at an earlier age in the child than in the parent.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4940   These two principles, namely, that slight variations generally appear at a not very early period of life, and are inherited at a corresponding not early period, explain, as I believe, all the above specified leading facts in embryology.

              " (extract-fr) part 109 of Darwin about: other hand, each other, same class, early period, corresponding ages, any metamorphosis, two principles, second stage, from each other, state of nature, habits of life, period of life, stages of development, later in life, undergo any metamorphosis, under the nauplius-form, not early period

@sen4942   Some authors who have written on Dogs maintain that the greyhound and bull-dog, though so different, are really closely allied varieties, descended from the same wild stock, hence I was curious to see how far their puppies differed from each other.

