@sen5060   for instance, the digit of an adult animal was used less and less during many generations, owing to some change of habits, or if an organ or gland was less and less functionally exercised, we may infer that it would become reduced in size in the adult descendants of this animal, but would retain nearly its original standard of development in the embryo.

              " (extract-fr) part 112 of Darwin about: distinct species, same species, natural selection, slight variations, early age, common parents, this difficulty, from common parents

@sen5062   After an organ has ceased being used, and has become in consequence much reduced, how can it be still further reduced in size until the merest vestige is left, and how can it be finally quite obliterated?

